properties.Name: CustomerReceivershipProceeding
properties.Description:
Receivership is used to denote a situation in which a legal entity,  institution or enterprise is being held by a receiver. 

A receiver is a legal person that has custodial responsibility for the property of others, which may include both tangible and intangible assets and rights.

There are various types of receiver appointments that may exist:

1.  A receiver appointed by a (government) regulator pursuant to a statute
2.  A privately-appointed receiver 
3.  A court-appointed receiver.

Columns.Name: ReceivershipProceedingId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Receivership Proceeding.

Columns.Name: ReceiverName
Columns.Description: The name of the court-appointed officer or business that acts as a receiver to identify, protect or liquidate debtor assets to benefit the creditor(s).

Columns.Name: PeriodStartDate
Columns.Description: The starting period date for which the Receiver is in charge of the Creditors business or assets.

Columns.Name: PeriodEndDate
Columns.Description: The ending period date for which the Receiver is in charge of the Creditors business or assets.

Columns.Name: EffectiveDate
Columns.Description: The date that the receivership is in effect.

Columns.Name: ReceivershipProceedingTypeId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Receivership Proceeding Type.

Columns.Name: CustomerId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Customer.

There are various types of receiver appointments that may exist:

2.  A privately-appointed receiver
